Votes don't help the author, so I've vowed to always leave a comment with mine, at the very least whenever I rate an article negatively. If you feel the same, help out by leaving critique with more of your votes. Comment follows:

suit

suit

suit

suit

This isn't an SCP. The anomaly, from the perspective of the Foundation, is poorly-defined if at all -  is all we get. The containment procedures don't really imply that 5353 is ever intended to be contained, in fact it almost feels like it's lampshading the fact that this isn't really an SCP. The format isn't justified. I actually think this would work much better as a PoI report, and all you'd need to cut is the SCP boilerplate.

I thought both of the incident logs were particularly compelling, and I really enjoyed both the white suit's monologue and the following counterattack by Nobody. Playing the two of them off of each other is an interesting take, and the swing from  was effective. I'm left doubting everything about either of them. The note at the end gives me the impression that the man in the white suit is what Nobody becomes after they're not Nobody anymore. If that's the case then they're both sort of meta-compulsion victims, and they're both as bad as each other.

+block

–block


However, I thought the content surrounding the incident logs wasn't that interesting, and served as a poor framing device. I wasn't able to find clear connections between the different events in the tables, so none of them meant anything to me, they were just filler to add space between the incidents. It's a shame that the best content of the article is buried in collapsibles.

It's also a little frustrating that this article feels like it's simply observing what's happening. The article feels too attached to the status quo, presenting the interaction between the white suit and Nobody as an immutable universal truth, when it could have been an opportunity for the Foundation to disrupt. The story is summarised, but it's not interacted with; the Foundation has no agency and the article feels passive as a result. Maliz is forced to play along to the white suit/Nobody's rules - not once but twice - and all she can do is ask a question every now and then. She  all by herself? What did she expect?

The formatting echoes my concerns. This is an SCP document, so I don't know why the Nobody theme is applied to it. The clearance level header is huge, the bottom of the logo touching the bottom of my laptop screen, and all that screen space is used to add nothing at all to the article.

Overall, it's a -1 from me, although there are gold nuggets in the collapsibles that are weighed down by everything else.





